\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\fs28 Introduction:\par
\fs24\tab Online credit card fraud is a type of cybercrime that involves the theft of credit card information from unsuspecting victims. Cybercriminals use various methods to steal credit card details, including phishing, malware, and hacking. The attackers then use the stolen information to make unauthorized purchases or transfer funds from the victim's account. In this case study, we will analyze a real-life scenario of online credit card fraud and the Indian laws that will be implemented on the attacker.\par
\fs28\par
About the Fraud:\par
\fs24\tab Mr. Sharma is a software engineer who lives in Mumbai, India. He recently noticed that his credit card has been charged for several unauthorized transactions. Upon checking his credit card statements, he found out that a total of Rs. 1,00,000 has been fraudulently charged on his credit card. Mr. Sharma immediately contacted his bank to report the fraud and canceled his credit card. The bank conducted an investigation and found out that the fraudsters had used Mr. Sharma's credit card information to purchase electronic items online.\par
\par
\tab The bank then contacted the cybercrime department of Mumbai Police, and an FIR (First Information Report) was lodged against the fraudsters. The police started their investigation and found out that the attackers had gained access to Mr. Sharma's credit card information through a phishing email. The email contained a link that led Mr. Sharma to a fake website that looked like the bank's official website. The website asked Mr. Sharma to enter his credit card details to verify his account, and the attackers were able to steal his information.\par
\par
\tab The police then tracked down the IP address used to access Mr. Sharma's account and found out that it belonged to a cybercafe in Delhi. The police conducted a raid and arrested the \par

\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qc 2\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1 cybercafe owner, who was found to be involved in the online credit card fraud. The police also seized several laptops, mobile phones, and other devices used by the attackers to carry out the fraud.\par
\f1\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qc\f2\fs28\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1 Laws implemented on the Attacker:\par
\fs24\tab In India, cybercrime is governed by the Information Technology Act, 2000 (IT Act) and the Indian Penal Code (IPC). The IT Act provides for the punishment of various cybercrimes, including hacking, phishing, and identity theft. The IPC also covers cybercrime under various sections such as cheating, fraud, and forgery.\par
\par
\tab In this case, the attackers used phishing to steal Mr. Sharma's credit card information, which is covered under section 66D of the IT Act. The section provides for punishment for cheating by impersonation using a computer resource, and the punishment is imprisonment of up to three years and/or a fine of up to Rs.1 lakh.\par
\par
\tab The attackers also committed the offense of cheating under section 420 of the IPC, which provides for punishment for cheating and dishonestly inducing delivery of property. The punishment for this offense is imprisonment of up to seven years and/or a fine.\par
\fs28\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1\qc 3\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa200\sl360\slmult1 Conclusion:\par
\fs24\tab Online credit card fraud is a growing threat in the digital age. It is essential for individuals to be aware of the various methods used by cybercriminals to steal credit card information and take necessary precautions to prevent such fraud. It is also important for banks and financial institutions to have robust security measures in place to prevent online credit card fraud. The Indian laws related to cybercrime are strict and provide for severe punishment for offenders. In this case, the attackers were caught and punished for their crimes, which should serve as a warning to others who might contemplate such offenses in the future.\par

