\fs28 About the Fraud:\par
\fs24 Background:\par
\tab Megan Meier was a 13-year-old girl from Missouri, USA, who struggled with depression and attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD). She befriended a boy named Josh Evans on MySpace, who claimed to be a 16-year-old boy from a nearby town. Megan and Josh exchanged messages on MySpace for several weeks and became close friends. However, Josh's messages suddenly turned hostile, and he started bullying and harassing Megan. The cyberbullying became so severe that Megan committed suicide by hanging herself in her bedroom closet.\par
\par
Investigation:\par
\tab After Megan's suicide, the police launched an investigation into the incident. They discovered that Josh Evans was not a real person but a fictitious online persona created by Lori Drew, a neighbor of Megan's. Lori Drew and her daughter created the Josh Evans account on MySpace to spy on Megan and bully her. Lori Drew was charged with violating the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA) for creating a fake MySpace profile to harass and bully Megan.\par
\par

